observations.recommendation:
Conduct a gender analysis of their programs and projects through the administration of the HGDG tool to be able to incorporate the PPAs that address gender issues in the GPB as well as mainstreaming in the agency operations so that the formulation, implementation, evaluation, and accounting of results of the LGU’s annual GPB and GAD AR will be in order;

Build capabilities through trainings to deepen their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools among others; and

Submit the DILG-reviewed GPB and GAD AR within the period required by Part V of COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management oversee the adherence to the pertinent provisions of NGAS Manual for LGUs and applicable policies and guidelines on the accounting and management of inventory to ensure the reliability and fair presentation of the balances in the financial statements.

In particular, we recommended that Management direct:
The Municipal Accountant to institute measures to ensure that inventory items received as donations are properly recorded and accounted for in the books;
The Inventory Committee to undertake physical inventory every six months, as required by the Manual, and submit the RPCI in order to ascertain the correctness of the inventory;
The GSO to properly maintain and update stock cards for all inventory items, to facilitate the review, physical count, and reconciliation of inventories. Likewise, prepare the SSMI, based on the RIS, to be used as basis for the recording in the books; and
Instruct the Municipal Health Officer and heads of all other concerned departments who are receiving goods-in-kind from National Government Agencies or from any source, to inform and coordinate with the GSO of such goods, before issuance to the concerned department or end-user. The GSO shall thereafter furnish the accounting department the necessary documents on the receipt and issuance for proper recording in the books of accounts.

We, therefore, recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant recognize and record the differences noted in the Accumulated Depreciation as of December 31, 2024 totaling ₱175,478.30;
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer improve coordination and establish a reporting mechanism on the status of ongoing constructions-in-progress and completed projects to prevent delays in recognition of the same to their appropriate accounts and to recognize the same even in the event of non-availability of actual billings from contractors;
Inventory Committee verify all donated assets against physical inventory records and obtain proper documentation; and
Municipal Accountant recognize all donated PPE as LGU assets and ensure proper valuation.

the Municipal Accountant revert to Cash in Bank- LCCA account the equivalent amount of stale checks totaling ₱47,500.00 in compliance with Item 2 of Section 59, Volume I of NGAS Manual for LGU;

If the checks are about to be considered as stale, the Municipal Treasurer send written notice to the payee on the existence of the check one month before the check becomes stale; and

If the check is already stale at the hands of the payee and presented for replacement, cancel the check on its face and shall be presented on the RCI after the last check issued for the period indicated in the report, and issue a replacement check accordingly.

MPDC initiate close coordination with the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant for the proper monitoring of project implementation and the provision of all the necessary information in the Status Report of Government PPAs before submission to the Audit Team.

Municipal Engineer require timely implementation of PPAs in coordination with the MPDC under their responsibility at all times;

MPDC and Municipal Engineer provide the Audit Team joint satisfactory explanation on the delayed implementation of the project as noted by the Local Chief Executive.

We recommended that the:

Local Chief Executive ensure the optimum utilization of the 20% DF by promptly implementing the priority development projects as reflected in its duly approved local development plans and establish the effective and efficient implementation of the projects to maximize the developmental benefits for the intended beneficiaries;

MPDC (i) initiate close coordination with the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant for the proper monitoring of project implementation and the provision of all the necessary information in the Status Report of Government PPAs before submission to the Audit Team; 

Municipal Engineer (i) require timely implementation of PPAs in coordination with the MPDC under their responsibility at all times; and

MPDC and Municipal Engineer (i) provide the Audit Team joint satisfactory explanation on the delayed implementation of the projects as noted by the Local Chief Executive.

Therefore, we recommended the following:

The Municipality to create new ordinances to increase its resources and to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to devise a plan to facilitate the collection of taxes to increase the revenue for a more efficient and effective implementation of its development plans, program objectives and priorities;



The Local Chief Executive to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to send demand letters to delinquent taxpayers and conduct an information campaign to all real property owners within the Municipality with emphasis of granting discounts when paid before due dates and the possibility of losing their property for not paying at all;

The Municipal Treasurer, in the exercise of his visitorial function, to look into the completeness of the books of accounts by the establishments;

Appropriate sanctions, as defined in the Revenue Code of the Municipality, to be imposed on taxpayers not complying with the rules and regulations on business taxation;

The concerned Management officials to revisit the provisions of the Revenue Code to come up with possible amendments that would redound to the best interest of the Municipality and the citizenry without going beyond the provisions and requirements of the LGC and its IRR; and

In order to fully address the revenue concerns, the concerned officials to gather information on the new and emerging businesses, profession or occupation for possible updating of the Municipality’s Revenue Code after series of public consultations and hearings.

submit written explanations from the accountable officers why the properties were not included in the count, and why the MGSO issued clearances despite failure of the AOs to surrender or make proper accounting of the municipal properties officially issued to them;
mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items and locate those missing that could shed light to the unreconciled balances between their records;
strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records of the accounting, the property and actual inventory results;
investigate the causes for the missing/unaccounted PPE items including those not found on site and identify the persons deemed liable thereof; and
continue to prepare and maintain property cards and property ledger cards

We recommended to the Management the following:
The Municipal Treasurer furnish at the beginning of the year a certified list of taxpayers with due and collectible for the year to the Municipal Accountant based on the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card;
The Municipal Accountant record the Real Property Tax/Special Education Tax Receivables based on the Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card;
The Municipal Accountant make a proper reconciliation of Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivables accounts with the record of the Municipal Treasurer; and
The Municipal Treasurer send demand letters to delinquent taxpayers and conduct an information campaign to all real property owners within the Municipality with emphasis of granting discounts when paid before due dates and the possibility of losing their property for not paying at all.

We recommended to the Management the following:
Utilize the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund in accordance with the approved Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Plans as incorporated in the local development plan and annual work and financial plan;
To desist in re-aligning current year appropriations for LDRRM Fund;
The Municipal Accountant recognize purchase equipment in accordance with Item 5.1.7 of COA-Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; and
To create Municipality’s Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office, under the Office of the Municipal Mayor pursuant to Section 21 of RA 10121.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
assess if there is really a need for consultants with the following considerations (i) engage only experts in their respective fields by considering the desired expertise, which is not available among the regular staff, in hiring consultant;  ; (ii) observe rules and regulations on the hiring of consultants as provided by IRR of RA No. 9184 and COA Circular 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012; 

specify the consultants’ duties/functions in the contracts as bases in the enforcement of their deliverables with the end in view to maximizing the worth of hiring said consultants and minimizing monetary losses to the Municipality;

If warranted, amend the contracts of the consultants to properly match that of the needs of the LCE or any officials needing assistance thereof to eliminate the nature of hiring said consultants;

ensure that payments for consultancy services are supported with adequate documentation by the Municipal Accountant before processing and payment of the claims for wages/salaries of the consultants to avoid Notice of Suspension/Disallowance in audit; and

evaluate and utilize the skills and talents of their regular employees to cut cost and to boost their morale; Likewise, utilize the services of the casual employees in discharging regular/ordinary services to compensate and maximize  the costs of their employment

We likewise recommended that the Human Resource Management Officer clearly facilitate and define the works or activities which could only be accomplished through hiring of consultants, incorporate them in the contracts and made them the bases to justify the need for consultancy services.
